.SH NAME
HTMLElement.offsetHeight \- HTMLElement: offsetHeight property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]HTMLElement.offsetHeight\f[B]\f[R] read\-only property
returns the height of an element, including vertical padding and
borders, as an integer.
.PP
Typically, \f[CR]offsetHeight\f[R] is a measurement in pixels of the
element\[cq]s CSS height, including any borders, padding, and horizontal
scrollbars (if rendered).
It does not include the height of pseudo\-elements such as
\f[CR]::before\f[R] or \f[CR]::after\f[R].
For the document body object, the measurement includes total linear
content height instead of the element\[cq]s CSS height.
Floated elements extending below other linear content are ignored.
.PP
If the element is hidden (for example, by setting
\f[CR]style.display\f[R] on the element or one of its ancestors to
\f[CR]\[dq]none\[dq]\f[R]), then \f[CR]0\f[R] is returned.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] This property will round the value to an integer.
If you need a fractional value, use
\f[CR]element.getBoundingClientRect()\f[R].
.RE
.SH VALUE
A number.
.SH EXAMPLES
